    "body": "### Describe the bug\r\n\r\nWhen I passed a very large bytes data into a function, the data became corrupted. The data is also corrupted differently everytime. Sometimes due to the way the bytes is corrupted, my programs throws a bus error.\r\n\r\nThis only happens when I pass the data into a `def` function, not a `cdef` function. I isolated the error making sure it has nothing to do with OpenGL. It also has nothing to do with data conversion between `bytes` and `unsigned char *`. This is because if i simply change `cdef update_data` to `def update_data`, the code breaks.\r\n\r\nContext:\r\n```python\r\n# python file\r\n\r\ntexture_1 = texture.load(\"imgs/test3.png\")\r\n# then I draw the texture\r\n...\r\n```\r\n```cython\r\n# cython file\r\n\r\ndef load(str filepath, bint resize_nearest=False):\r\n    stbi_set_flip_vertically_on_load(1)\r\n\r\n    cdef int width, height, n\r\n    cdef unsigned char *data = stbi_load(filepath.encode(), &width, &height, &n, 4) # load data from image\r\n\r\n    # p_data = list(data[200000 * 4:200010 * 4])\r\n    # print(p_data)\r\n\r\n    if data == NULL:\r\n        texture = None\r\n        raise RuntimeError(f\"Failed to load texture at {filepath}\")\r\n    else:\r\n        texture = Texture(width, height, data, resize_nearest, filepath)  # error is here\r\n        # texture.update_data(data)  # uncomment to upload correct data\r\n        stbi_image_free(data)\r\n\r\n    return texture\r\n\r\n\r\ncdef class Texture:\r\n\r\n    def __init__(\r\n        self, int width, int height, bytes py_data=None, bint resize_nearest=False\r\n        , str path=None\r\n    ):\r\n        # by this point py_data is already corrupted\r\n...\r\n        cdef unsigned char *data\r\n        if py_data is None:\r\n            data = NULL\r\n        else:\r\n            data = py_data\r\n\r\n        # p_data = list(data[200000 * 4:200010 * 4])\r\n        # print(p_data)\r\n...\r\n        glTexImage2D(\r\n            GL_TEXTURE_2D, 0, GL_RGBA, width, height, 0, GL_RGBA, GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE, data\r\n        )  # pass data into graphics memory, which is corrupted\r\n...\r\n\r\n    cdef update_data(self, unsigned char *data):\r\n        glBindTexture(GL_TEXTURE_2D, self.texture_id)\r\n        glTexSubImage2D(\r\n            GL_TEXTURE_2D, 0, 0, 0, self.width, self.height, GL_RGBA, GL_UNSIGNED_BYTE, data\r\n        )  # update the data, is corrupted depending if this function is cdef or def\r\n...\r\n```\r\nIf I don't call `update_data`, or call it and change `cdef update_data` to `def update_data`, my texture draws out like this:\r\n<img width=\"1312\" alt=\"image\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/83525937/229330587-39ce4fe9-7ead-4af2-81cd-493ffc62a6f4.png\">\r\n\r\nIf I call `update_data`, the texture draws properly:\r\n<img width=\"1312\" alt=\"image\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/83525937/229330618-910b2ad5-346c-49a1-b0fd-0f640382912a.png\">\r\n\r\nI did some further investigation by printing the data, before and after the function, and I can confirm there is a corruption.\r\nThis is a result of the print statements if I uncomment them:\r\n```\r\n[255, 0, 0, 255, 255, 0, 0, 255, 255, 0, 0, 255, 255, 0, 0, 255, 255, 0, 0, 255, 255, 0, 0, 255, 255, 0, 0, 255, 255, 0, 0, 255, 255, 0, 0, 255, 255, 0, 0, 255]\r\n[108, 101, 0, 95, 95, 108, 111, 111, 112, 48, 95, 49, 55, 55, 95, 114, 117, 108, 101, 0, 95, 95, 103, 97, 116, 104, 101, 114, 95, 49, 55, 56, 95, 114, 117, 108, 101, 0, 95, 95]\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\r\n\r\nI honestly do not know the specific circumstances that make this happen, but I'll lay it out so it matches my code.\r\n```cython\r\n# a.pyx\r\n\r\ndef foo():\r\n    data: bytes = # very large\r\n    Bar(data)\r\n\r\ncdef class Bar:\r\n    def __init__(self, bytes data):\r\n        pass\r\n```\r\n```python\r\nimport a\r\n\r\na.foo()\r\n```\r\n\r\n`data` gets corrupted when passed in the init function\r\n\r\n### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\nData shouldn't be corrupted when passed into another function.\r\n\r\n### OS\r\n\r\nmacOS\r\n\r\n### Python version\r\n\r\n3.11.2\r\n\r\n### Cython version\r\n\r\n3.0.0b2\r\n\r\n### Additional context\r\n\r\nThis is part of a 2D graphics library I'm working on, so the program can be run if needed in `examples/main.py` [here](https://github.com/williamhCode/cyclone/tree/110bf2421111d5a7a1c0118242439cfa37b696e7).  \r\nUncomment line 19 in `cyclone/texture.pyx` to get make the bug happen.  \r\nNote: I've only built the project on macOS so I don't know if it works on windows/linux.",
